I see you found the `nashorn-maven-plugin` to run Javascript. But the `ScriptEngine` 
 JS implementation has since been removed from the JRE, so that plugin won&#39;t work from Java 15 onwards unless you find a way to add the JS engine back to your classpath.

There is currently a more generic official maven plugin available to run small scripts in a very similar way. The [Apache Maven Scripting Plugin](https://maven.apache.org/plugins/maven-scripting-plugin/) can execute scripts in any `JSR223` compatible scripting language. 

The plugin uses the same [ScriptEngine](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/javax/script/ScriptEngine.html) mechanism, which relies on service discovery ([loading](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/ServiceLoader.html) a service provider interface). This means that it can use any compatible scripting language by placing a specific library on your classpath.

For more references on the library options you have, see the following questions:
 - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20013310/java-scriptengine-supported-languages
 - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11838369/where-can-i-find-a-list-of-available-jsr-223-scripting-languages

These also include code on how to list the currently available scripting languages (which is just JS for Java versions 8 to 15 if you don&#39;t add additional libraries).

I have successfully used this plugin with the language of my choice on Maven 3 and Java 17. See the full example below.

I would advice to use the `&lt;scriptFile&gt;` option if at all possible, so you don&#39;t have to maintain code in the pom file. But if you need to use any `${...}` variables you might not be able to use the file option. In that case you can use the `&lt;script&gt;` option. If needed you can include the CDATA marker to keep the XML valid.

The plugin does expose the entire `MavenProject` model and a logger, that should cover most needs. It gives access to all the project information, properties and the build environment. The following variables are bound by default for that purpose:
- `project` as [org.apache.maven.project.MavenProject](https://maven.apache.org/ref/3.3.9/apidocs/org/apache/maven/project/MavenProject.html)
- `log` as [org.apache.maven.plugin.logging.Log](https://maven.apache.org/ref/3.3.9/maven-plugin-api/apidocs/org/apache/maven/plugin/logging/Log.html)

In my case i used `Beanshell`, and the plugin setup looks like this:
```xml
 &lt;!-- Scripting Plugin: run ScriptEngine compatible scripts --&gt;
&lt;plugin&gt;
	&lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.maven.plugins&lt;/groupId&gt;
	&lt;artifactId&gt;maven-scripting-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
	&lt;version&gt;3.0.0&lt;/version&gt;
	&lt;executions&gt;
		&lt;execution&gt;
			&lt;id&gt;run-script&lt;/id&gt;
			&lt;phase&gt;compile&lt;/phase&gt;
			&lt;goals&gt;
				&lt;goal&gt;eval&lt;/goal&gt;
			&lt;/goals&gt;
		&lt;/execution&gt;
	&lt;/executions&gt;
	&lt;configuration&gt;
		&lt;engineName&gt;beanshell&lt;/engineName&gt;
		&lt;!-- &lt;scriptFile&gt;use this when possible; no code in the POM is preferred&lt;/scriptFile&gt; --&gt;
		&lt;script&gt;
			log.info(&quot;Hello from &quot; + project.getArtifact());
		&lt;/script&gt;
	&lt;/configuration&gt;
	&lt;dependencies&gt;
		&lt;!-- Script Engine: Beanshell --&gt;
		&lt;dependency&gt;
			&lt;groupId&gt;org.apache-extras.beanshell&lt;/groupId&gt;
			&lt;artifactId&gt;bsh&lt;/artifactId&gt;
			&lt;version&gt;2.0b6&lt;/version&gt;
		&lt;/dependency&gt;
	&lt;/dependencies&gt;
&lt;/plugin&gt;
```
You can use any `id` and `phase` you like in the `execution` element.

By changing the `dependency` and `engineName` you can use any other compatible scripting language.

This gives the following output in the maven build log:
```
[INFO] --- maven-scripting-plugin:3.0.0:eval (run-script) @ tests ---
[INFO] Hello from local:tests:jar:1.0
```

