The regular way to define a custom ordering in Java is via a [Comparator](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Comparator.html) instance. This object can be plugged into the sorting routines of eg [`Arrays`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#sort(T[],%20java.util.Comparator)) or [`Collections`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#sort(java.util.List,%20java.util.Comparator)).

In Java 8 for example you can sort your array like so:
```java
Arrays.sort(wonderArray, Comparator.comparingInt(wonder -&gt; wonder.hospitality));
``` 

In Java 7 or before, you can do it with an anonymous class: 
```java
Arrays.sort(wonderArray, new Comparator&lt;Wonder&gt;() {
  @Override public int compareTo(Wonder w1, Wonder w2) {
    return Integer.compare(w1.hospitality, w2.hospitality);
  }
});
```

